'use strict';(function(){const indexCfg={cache:true};indexCfg.doc={id:'id',field:['title','content'],store:['title','href'],};const index=FlexSearch.create('balance',indexCfg);window.bookSearchIndex=index;index.add({'id':0,'href':'/','title':"",'content':"这个博客主要是用于学习、总结和分享知识。\n内容会使用中文或者英文。\n如果有任何错误，敬请指正。\nThis blog is for learning, summary and sharing knowledge and writting in Chinese and English.\nPlease be free to correct my error.\n"});index.add({'id':1,'href':'/numerical/about/','title':"About",'content':"该目录下的内容主要是关于数值计算。\nThe content under this menu is mainly about the numerical computing. Please be free to correct my error.\n"});index.add({'id':2,'href':'/numerical/','title':"Numericals",'content':""});index.add({'id':3,'href':'/numerical/Finite-Volume-Method/About/','title':"About",'content':"有限体积法（Fininte Volume Method, FVM）是一种基于守恒律的数值解法。\n FVM将求解区域离散为网格（可以是结构化也可以是非结构化类型），然后将其划分为一系列不重合的控制体，对待解的微分方程在单个控制体内进行体积分，利用斯托克斯定理得到微分方程相应的积分形式，然后对方程进行离散求解。\n 参考书目：\n Leveque, 2004, Finite Volume Methods for Hyperbolic Equations. F. Moukalled, L. Mangani and M. Darwish, 2016, The Finite Volume Method in Computational Fluid Dynamics.  "});index.add({'id':4,'href':'/posts/about/','title':"About",'content':"write about something!\n"});index.add({'id':5,'href':'/numerical/Finite-Volume-Method/Acoustics-boundary/','title':"Acoustics boundary",'content':"The systems of equations, such as acoustics, can have positive and negative eigenvalues, so that each boundary will typiccally have both incoming and outcoming characteristics.\nConsider the acoustics equations\n$$ p_t+K_0u_x=0 $$ $$ \\rho_0u_t+p_x=0, $$ with a variety of different boundary conditions.\n1.Nonreflecting Boundary Conditions\nWe want to impose nonreflectiong boundary conditions (absorbing boundary conditions) at points $x=a$ and $x=b$ that do not introduce spurious reflections of the outgoing acoustic waves. We can simply set $$ Q_0^n=Q_1^n,\\ Q_{-1}^n=Q_1^n $$ in each time step.\n2.Incoming Waves\nWe want to impose the boundary condition $$ \\omega^2(a,t)=sin(\\omega t) $$ as the incoming signal, together with nonreflection of any outgoing signal that has been generated within the domain. If we decompose $Q_1$ into $Q_1=W_1^1r^1+W_1^2r^2$, then the ghost cell value $Q_0$ should be set as $$Q_0=W_1^1r^1+sin(\\omega (t_n+\\Delta x/2c_0))r^2.$$ We could first extrapolate the whole vector $Q$ and then reset the $\\omega^2 $ compenent, setting $$Q_0=Q_1+(sin(\\omega (t_n+\\Delta x/2c_0))-W_1^2)r^2.$$ For a larger systems of m equations, we want to impose an incoming wave in only one characteristic family, e.g., $$\\omega_j(a,t)=g_0(t),$$ wit some j. Then we could set $$Q_0=Q_1+[g_0(t_n+\\Delta x/2\\lambda^j)-W_1^j]r^j,$$ where $W_1^j=l^jQ_1$ is the eigen-coefficient of $r^j$ in $Q_1$ and $\\lambda^j$ is the corresponding eigen-value.\n3.Solid Walls\nFor a solid wall at $x=a$ this is $$u(a,t)=0,$$\n4.Oscillating Walls\nFor very small-amplitude motions we can use this boundary condition $$u(a,t)=U(t),$$ to simulate the vibrating wall. We can implement this by setting the following ghost-cell values:\n\r$$\r\\left.\r\\begin{array}{l}\r\\text{for}\u0026Q_0:\\ p_0=p_1,\\ u_0=2U(t_n)-u_1,\\\\\r\\text{for}\u0026Q_{-1}:\\ p_{-1}=p_2,\\ u_{-1}=2U(t_n)-u_2.\r\\end{array}\r\\right.\r$$\r\r"});index.add({'id':6,'href':'/categories/','title':"Categories",'content':""});index.add({'id':7,'href':'/numerical/Finite-Volume-Method/Convergence/','title':"Convergence",'content':"For a finite volume method, we might want to compare $Q^n_1$ with\n\r$$\r\\begin{equation}\rq^n_i=\\frac {1}{\\Delta x}\\int_{x_{i-1/2}}^{x_{i+1/2}} q(x,t_n) \\,{\\rm d}x.\r\\end{equation}\r$$\r\rIf the function $q(x,t)$ is sufficiently smooth, then the pointwise value agrees with the cell average to $\\cal O(\\Delta x^2)$. It is reasonable to assume that the ratio $\\Delta t/\\Delta x$ is fixed. Then we can speak of letting $\\Delta t \\to 0$ to refine the grid, and speak of convergence with order s if the errors vanish like $\\cal O(\\Delta t^s)$ or $\\cal O(\\Delta x^s)$.\n1.Norms\nThe standard set of norms most commonly used are the p-norms\n\r$$\r\\|E\\|_p=\\left(\\Delta x\\sum_{i=-\\infty}^\\infty|E_i|^p\\right)^{1/p}.\r$$\r\rNote that, commmonly, there is no $\\Delta x$ in norms. We say that the method is convergent at time T in the norm $|\\cdot|$ if\n$$ \\lim_{\\Delta t \\to 0_{N\\Delta t=T}}|E^N|=0. $$\nThe method is said to be accurate of order s if $$ |E^N|=\\cal O(\\Delta t^s)\\quad \\text{as }\\Delta t\\to 0. $$ We can use the max norm (or $\\infty$-norm) to measure the error $$ |E|_{\\infty}=\\max_{-\\infty\u0026lt;\\infty}|E|. $$\n"});index.add({'id':8,'href':'/docs/','title':"Docs",'content':""});index.add({'id':9,'href':'/posts/','title':"Posts",'content':""});index.add({'id':10,'href':'/tags/','title':"Tags",'content':""});})();